t non-success wires downward with higher Y values instead. I'm going to classify each wire as success or non-success, then offset the bezier curve control points for non-success edges to arc them below the main path, and add CSS classes to style them differently.\n\nImplementing wire classification... Still writing the wire rendering...\n\nActually, I'm realizing the bezier curve approach needs adjustment—the control points should be positioned so the curve bows outward from the main flow, and I need to reconsider how the Y-coordinates work for the control points to achieve that effect properly. Still writing the wire logic... ier curves below the main path\n3. For terminal wires: offset non-success wires (typically to \"abort\") below, and keep success wires (typically to \"done\") centered\n4. Add CSS classes for visual distinction (maybe slightly different stroke style for non-success wires)\n\nActually, I realize the terminal merge pattern already handles some of this. Let me focus on making the normal wire routing smarter.\n\nLet me think about what the actual offset amount should be. Given:\n- nodeH = 48\n- nodeGap = 28\n- So total per-node vertical space is about 76px\n\nAn offset of about 30-40px below center should be enough to visually separate the wires without going too far.\n\nBut actually, for wires from the same source to different targets, the Y coordinates of the targets are different, so they're somewhat separated already. The main collision issue is when both a success wire and a failure wire originate from the same step—they start at the same point and could overlap before diverging. My solution is to apply a downward bezier curve to non-success wires by offsetting their control points below the direct path.\n\nFor terminal wires, I'll keep \"done\" wires centered and offset \"abort\" wires downward. The core strategy is to group wires by source node, give success wires the center path, and route other wires below.\n\nLet me start implementing this. I'll modify the wire rendering logic to apply these offsets based on the wire type and result. Implementing the wire separation logic now...\n\nI need to add a helper to identify success results, then apply vertical offsets to non-success wires in both normal and terminal wire drawing—offsetting by about 30-40px when multiple wires converge on the same target. I'll also add a CSS class to style non-success edges distinctly, and skip the offset when there's only a single wire from a step since there's no overlap to worry about. main flow. I'm creating a helper function to identify success results, then offsetting all non-success wires visually to show they're alternate paths rather than the primary route. For terminal wires, I need to adjust where the merge collectors position themselves based on whether they're on the success path or not.\n\nLet me work through a concrete example with multiple steps flowing to either done or abort terminals—the layout algorithm already separates them vertically, but I need to handle cases where wires cross over each other. which is ordered first), and \"abort\" would be ordered second (connected from step1 and step2).\n\nPositions:\n- step1: (30, ~centered)\n- step2: (30+180+120=330, ~centered)\n- done: (330+180+120=630, ~top)\n- abort: (630, ~bottom)\n\nThe success path goes step1 -> step2 -> done: roughly a straight line through the center/top.\nThe failure path goes step1 -> abort and step2 -> abort: curves going from center to bottom.\n\nIn this case, the curves already separate somewhat because abort is below done. But the failure wires from step1 to abort would cross over step2, and the wire from step2 to abort would be a short downward curve. These could overlap with the success wire from step1 to step2 if they're at similar Y positions.\n\nSo I need to push the failure wires' curves below the main flow by applying a downward offset to their bezier control points. I'll use a fixed offset of around 30-40px for non-success wires to keep things simple and prevent overlaps.\n\nImplementing wire offset logic... If there are multiple non-success wires from the same source, offset each one by a multiple.\n\nActually, this could get complex fast. Let me focus on the most common case and keep it clean.\n\nMy simplified approach: for each source step, count the outgoing wires. If there's more than one, success wires get center routing while non-success wires get offset routing with a fixed amount like 35px below center. I'll apply the same logic to terminal wires.\n\nThe key modifications are in the normWires bezier curves, the termWires handling for \"abort\" wires below the main flow, and single terminal wires. I also want to add a different colored arrowhead for non-success wires.\n\nLooking at the current code structure, I see there's one arrowhead marker and a dag-edge class for all edges. I need to add a new arrowhead-nonsuccess marker with a failure color, a dag-edge-nonsuccess CSS class, and implement clean offset logic.\n\nWriting the control point offset logic... Finishing the bezier curve definition for non-success wires. I'm offsetting both control points downward by 35 pixels to create a visible dip in the curve, which should provide clear visual separation between success and failure paths. For the label positioning, I'll shift it down by the same offset amount so it stays centered on the curved wire regardless of the node distance.\n\nNow for terminal wires, I need to apply similar logic. For wires going to \"abort,\" I'll offset the curves below the main flow, while \"done\" wires stay centered. The merge pattern for terminal wires works by collecting curves at a merge point before connecting to the terminal, so I can apply the same bezier offset technique to make non-success terminal wires arc downward before reaching the merge line.\n\nExamining the terminal wire code... Writing SVG curves for merge patterns...\n\nI'm realizing the core issue: when multiple connectors merge 