rge pattern below the center line, then drawing the individual curves from each source point to that offset merge line.\n\nStill writing SVG paths... I need to reconsider how offsetting the curve endpoints affects the merge pattern—if each source connects at its own Y position to the merge line, and I offset those endpoints, the vertical collector line will naturally span the full range from the topmost to bottommost point, so the merge dots and terminal connection should still work correctly.\n\nActually, a cleaner approach would be to offset the entire merge collector bus downward as a unit, then draw curves from the sources to this offset merge line and finally connect it to the terminal, which would visually group the failure paths together below the main flow.\n\nThe issue is that this requires different Y values for each source's bus, so I'm going to simplify: offset the bezier control points for non-success wires and add a CSS class for styling, while for merge patterns I'll make the curves bow through an offset Y position so they visually separate from the success path.\n\nWriting the implementation... I'm thinking through the offset direction for non-success wires—if they go downward, I should push them further down, but if they go upward, I might want to pull them back toward the center instead. The barycenter ordering usually places failure targets below success targets anyway, so this adaptive approach should handle most cases well.\n\nActually, I'm going to keep it simple and just use a fixed downward offset. It'll work for the vast majority of cases and avoids unnecessary complexity. The goal is to push non-success wires away from the success path, which is the core workflow, so pushing them below makes sense.\n\nImplementing the helper function now...\n\nWriting the wire rendering logic... Writing SVG edge labels and terminal connections... Writing SVG paths... Writing SVG connector paths... Still writing SVG and styles...\n\nNow I need to increase the SVG height to account for the offset that might push curves beyond the current boundaries, so I'm adding padding to ensure everything fits. For testing, I should verify that the failure styling classes and markers are properly rendered in the output.\n\nLooking at the wire grouping logic, I realize that wires are already organized by their target terminal—\"done\" typically receives success wires while \"abort\" gets failures. But there could be edge cases like a failed step routing to \"done\", so I need to handle mixed success and non-success wires going to the same terminal, treating each wire individually rather than assuming all wires to a terminal have the same status. I'm realizing the cleanest approach is to check each wire individually—if a wire's result is non-success, I offset just that curve, while keeping the merge line itself centered. This way success wires to \"done\" stay aligned while failure wires get offset, even when they're in the same merge group.\n\nWriting the curve logic... Writing SVG merge paths... I'm double-checking whether the label placement formula actually aligns with the bezier curve's midpoint, since the exact center of a cubic bezier curve follows a specific mathematical formula rather than just the simple average of endpoints. I'm deciding that the label positioning is close enough with the current formula, so I'll stick with `(y1+y2)/2 + off - 6`. Now I need to update the SVG height calculation to account for the offset space and prevent clipping of the non-success curves at the bottom. Then I'll implement these changes as edits to the existing code and add test assertions for the new CSS classes and functionality. I'm realizing the CSS classes like `dag-edge-nonsuccess` will appear as string literals in the JavaScript code that's embedded in the HTML response, so checking for them in the body should work. The test workflow has both success and fail paths, so the offset logic will definitely be exercised and those strings should be present in the rendered output.\n\nNow I need to plan out the actual changes: I'll add the CSS styling for the non-success edge class to the stylesheet, then modify the JavaScript in the HTML template to introduce the helper function for detecting success results, calculate the offset for non-success wires, add the fail arrowhead marker to the SVG definitions, and apply the offset logic across all the different wire drawing scenarios—the normal wires, single terminal wires, and the multi-terminal merge patterns.\n\nI'm going to scope the helper function inside `showWorkflow` rather than globally, and I need to make sure the SVG height accounts for this offset as well. Let me trace through each section of the code that needs modification and apply the offset consistently across all wire drawing paths.\n\nWriting SVG marker code... Writing SVG paths... Writing SVG path code... Still writing SVG paths... Writing SVG merge visualization...\n\nNow I need to add the CSS styling for failed edges and update the test to verify the new classes and offset behavior are working correctly. Let me trace through the test workflow to make sure I'm handling both success and failure paths properly. Still writing test assertions...\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the CSS approach for non-success edges—I want them to stand out as failures with a red-tinted color and reduced opacity to keep them visually de-emphasized, so I'm defining a style that uses the failed badge color at 70% opacity.\n\nPlanning out the specific edits I need to make: adding the new CSS rule after the merge-dot style, inserting the nonsuccOffset variable in the JavaScript, and updating the edge-drawing logic to apply the styling based on success status. Still writing marker definitions... Writing SVG edge labels... Writing SVG edge labels... Writing SVG paths... Writing SVG path curves... Writing the curve paths... Still writing SVG code... Adding test assertions...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequen